7":"1254–1297","1256–1299":"1256–1299","29 Sep 1306":"29 September 1306","1297":"1297","1286":"1286","1274":"1274","1285":"1285","1370":"1370","1292":"1292","before 1305":"before 1305","1305":"1305","1279":"1279","1312":"1312","1256":"1256","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Croft, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Croft, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Ireland":"Ireland","Croft Castle, Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"Leominster, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Croft","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places, for example in Lincolnshire, Lancashire, Herefordshire, and North Yorkshire, all named with Old English <i>croft</i> ‘small arable enclosure (normally adjoining a house)’, or a topographic name for someone who lived by a croft, from Middle English <i>croft</i>.","English: possibly in some cases a variant of   Craft   2.","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . Compare   Kroft   and   Craft  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Craft","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>craft</i> ‘skillful, clever, learned’.","English: habitational name from Croft in Leicestershire. See also   Croft  .","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . See also   Croft  ."]},{"name":"Crate","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Surrey): from Middle English <i>crate</i> ‘hurdle, basket’, or occasionally perhaps from <i>crete</i> ‘cradle’, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such articles. Alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Croft   1."]},{"name":"Crofts","meanings":["English: variant of   Croft  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Groft","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Croft  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Hugh De Croft was born in 1274, in Leominster, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Croft, was 20 and his mother, Catherine Leominster, was 18. He married Maud Brian in 1305. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1317, in Ireland, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1274–1317":"1274–1317","1285–1312":"1285–1312","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","–1305":"–1305","1306–1370":"1306–1370","1254–1297":"1254–1297","1256–1299":"1256–1299","29 Sep 1306":"29. september 1306","1297":"1297","1286":"1286","1274":"1274","1285":"1285","1370":"1370","1292":"1292","before 1305":"enne 1305","1305":"1305","1279":"1279","1312":"1312","1256":"1256","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Croft, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Croft, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Croft Castle, Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"Leominster, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1274–1317":"1274–1317","1285–1312":"1285–1312","1292–Male":"1292–Kuollut","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","–1305":"–1305","1306–1370":"1306–1370","1254–1297":"1254–1297","1256–1299":"1256–1299","29 Sep 1306":"29. syyskuuta 1306","1297":"1297","1286":"1286","1274":"1274","1285":"1285","1370":"1370","1292":"1292","before 1305":"ennen vuotta 1305","1305":"1305","1279":"1279","1312":"1312","1256":"1256","1299":"1299","1254":"1254","1317":"1317","1306":"1306","Croft, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Croft, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ireland":"Irlanti","Croft Castle, Leominster, Herefordshire, England":"England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefords